John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, with this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in exams, strengthened by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30 000 students scattered throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service, both for students and parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for deepening their studies and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after theme in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can enter his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can enter his heart."
This quote reminds us that we cannot rely solely on English when we intend to create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of recent exams this year, we found that the languages are at the top of the tables, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum A classification.
These data, collected in the 74 schools under SCIS, show that 72% of the students obtained the maximum A score in mandarim, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are promoting foreign languages as vital competences that will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A survey by the UK Employment and Competence Commission in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for employers' difficulty in filling vacancies, 17% concerned the shortage of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities to demand language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with a skill for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person in front of competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and the French was the only language spoken by a ratio of two digits, 15%.
Therefore, investing in language teaching now is important for today's children.
The domain of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children with better chances of finding jobs with relevance.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as mandarim or Japanese.
Whatever the interest of your child, there will always be a set of languages to choose in independent schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the necessary skills for success, whatever the future holds for them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance to the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence for young Scottish people.
We have to do this.
