North Korea says "no thinking" to untrustworthy unilateral disarmament
The Minister for Foreign Affairs of North Korea stated to the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was exacerbating mistrust with the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons in those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as the interruption of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear testing centre and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the US there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way to proceed with our disarmament first."
Although Ri has recycled known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, within which North Korea would be rewarded as it made gradual steps, its statements appear significant insofar as they do not absolutely reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang's previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between a U.S. President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim committed to working towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has sought to achieve a formal end to the war in Korea from 1950-53, but the United States claims that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearization first" and increases the pressure level with sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive way, opposing itself until "declaration of the end of war," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the prolongation of sanctions is exacerbating our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been mentioned by the US leader in the United Nations at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and the South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the party concerned on this issue were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that guiding North Korea's rockets towards US territory was inevitable after Mr. President Mau' Trump called Kim the "man of rockets" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who had threatened to " utterly destroy" North Korea last year, commended Kim for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but stated that much still had to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea's denuclearisation.
On Wednesday, Trump stated that he did not have a timetable for this, stating that "it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
