The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their change in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, designated by HER2. These cells are then injected again into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancer," including those of the breast, ovary, lungs and also colorectals, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach that involves removing immune cells from patients and "teaching them" to attack cancer cells worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
