What is the Global Citizen Festival? Did you do anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, the city of New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual musical event with a list of extremely impressive stars that will work on an equally impressive mission: eradicate poverty in the world.
Already in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will host tens of thousands of people in Central Park's Great Revado, not only to attend the performances of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to strengthen awareness of the true goal of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a defense group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To receive a free ticket for the event (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) the viewers had to perform a series of tasks, or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, a telephone call or any other significant ways to increase awareness of the goal of ending poverty.
However, what was the degree of success of the Global Citizen in these 12 years in achieving its goal?
The idea of rewarding people with a free concert is a genuine way to persuade them to demand action, or is this just another case of "cliquetivism" - do we think it makes a difference to sign an online petition or send a tweet?
Global Citizen states that since 2011, it has registered more than 19 million "actions" of its supporters who have put pressure on it to achieve a number of different objectives.
These actions, according to the organization, contributed to world leaders announcing commitments and policies valued at more than 37 billion dollars, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from its actions, with at least $10 billion for those already disbursed or pledged.
The group estimates that the funds obtained have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people scattered around the world.
Some of the main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a partnership based in the United Kingdom bringing together investors and implementers committed to "helping children reach their full potential", which pledged to give Rwanda $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country. This after receiving more than 4700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like all of us, we can make the social injustice of undernutrition a footnote to history," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, to a crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group further stated that, after more than 5000 pressure actions on the United Kingdom to improve the nutrition of mothers and children, the government announced that it would finance a project, the Power of Nutrition, which will cover 5 million women and children, with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the website, "What makes you think that we can eradicate extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen answers: "It was a long and crooked way - sometimes we fell and failed.
But just like the great movements for civil and anti-apartheid rights that preceded us, because we are more powerful together.
