The first rescue of the trade war between the U.S. and China was insurgent, and although the end of the conflict is not in sight, from the perspective of the experts, the departure of the two countries can be beneficial to Beijing in the long term.
Donald Trump, President of the U.S.A., fired the first warning at the beginning of the year to tax important Chinese imports including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
This week was the stage of a significant worsening of the situation with the new rates to affect goods worth $200 billion ($150 billion), actually charging half of all goods sent by China to the United States.
Beijing has always retaliated in the same currency, recently raising the rates of 5 to 10 percent for US goods worth $60 billion.
China has committed itself to following the steps of the U.S. and it is unlikely that the second largest economy in the world will hesitate in the near future.
Making Washington back would mean succumbing to demands, but showing a public subservice to the U.S. would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, President of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing makes good use of its assets, the pressures imposed by the trade war with the U.S. can positively sustain China in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"In fact, the fact that an early political decision in Washington or Beijing could result in an economic crisis in both countries is much more dangerous than observers could ever have anticipated," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher dedicated to the study of Asia at the Center for New American Security, a reflection group.
Minister for Foreign Affairs states that Syria is ready for the return of refugees
Syria claims to be prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild a country devastated for more than seven long years of war.
In his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, the Minister for Foreign Affairs, Walid al-Moualem, said that the conditions of the country are improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to progress in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
There are now all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that have left because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people who have remained in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would gladly receive help for the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional assistance or aid from countries that sponsored the rebellion.
