Updated information about the Red Sea: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there was a decrease in Red Sea concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower proliferation of stains were identified in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The stain of the Red Sea extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less areas than last week.
The Red Sea was also seen in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded near or off the coast of Pinella County, low high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom to medium concentrations on Charlotte County, bottom to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations on Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritations in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritations in the northwest region of Florida.
